observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to:
a) Reassess and reconsider the internal controls, policies and procedures adopted by the Municipality in recognizing, monitoring, safeguarding and reporting of its Property, Plant and Equipment:
b) Intensify the institutionalization of an Inventory Committee to conduct actual physical inventory of its PPE annually, taking into consideration the required standards and procedures in Planning, Execution, and Reconciliation of GSO and Accounting records;
c) Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain and update the PPE ledger cards and the GSO of its property cards as control records to facilitate the regular reconciliation of records and investigate any discrepancy noted;
d) Ensure that all insurable physical assets are adequately and reliably protected against any damage to or loss of properties pursuant to Republic Act No. 656;
e) Facilitate the preparation of documentary requirements to secure the Transfer Certificates of Title (TCT) under the name of the Municipality of Matalam, Cotabato for all parcels of land to support claims of ownership and to avoid loss of properties in case other interested parties may claim the same in the future; and trace its records/documents to establish ownership of the parcels of land with incomplete data as to acquisition date and cost and if found to be legally owned by the Municipality, expedite the application for the land titles under the name of the Municipality of Matalam, Cotabato; and
f) Require the Municipal Accountant to recognize all completed Road Network Assets on cost or fair value whichever is applicable and direct the Municipal Accountant, the MGSO, the Municipal Engineer and the Inventory Committee to strictly perform their duties and responsibilities in the accounting and reporting of Local Road Network as mandated under COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
a) Strictly adhere to Item V of COA Circular No. 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014 doe the timely submission of the said reports to the COA audit team;
b) Require the Heads of implementing departments/offices to ensure that GAD projects, activities and programs are implemented as planned to attain the GAD objectives;
c) Maximize the utilization of the GAD funds through the implementation of GAD-related programs and projects in order to attain the objective for which funds were provided;
d) Comply with the requirement of Section 37 (C), Rule VI of RA No. 9710 or the Magna Carta of Women and Section 4.1A of PCW- DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01;
e) Require the GAD Focal Point System to (i) institutionalize the GAD database with adequate and systematically gathered sex-disaggregated data which will provide the bases for gender analysis, planning, programming and policy formulation; (ii) undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues and ensure that the projects, activities and programs are responsive to the said issues; and (iii) revisit Annex B of PCW- DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01, which identifies the data requirements for particular gender issues; and
f) Establish a GAD monitoring and evaluation system as required under Sections 3.4 and 5.1 of PCW- DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01.
